Aim   : Add a User, Network Settings, Change to static IP address, Disable IPv6 if not needed, Configure Services,

Display the list of services which are running, Stop and turn OFF auto-start setting for a service if you donâ€™t 
need it, Sudo Settings.
       
       
       
            

Step1 : Adding a user on terminal : 

 to add user : $sudo adduser <username>

in machine e.g :- $sudo adduser lsa_user


Step2:Network settings: The ip address . ethernet connections and other network connections  viewing command : $sudo ip a  //OR//  $sudo ip addr


Step:3Configuring services: services are also known as daemons which efficiently run in the background, services usually have a 'd' in last 

of their name to identify it is a daemon for example :- smbd , nmbd,etc

services can be view in the /etc/ folder as mostly the services  there for example: $sudo nano /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf 

Step 4:List of services running: command to list the currently active and running services:- $sudo systemc


Step5:
enable a service: $sudo systemctl enable <service_name>

syntax to start a service:-                 $sudo systemctl start <service_name>
syntax to check the status of a service:-    $sudo systemctl status <service_name>
syntax to stop a service:-                   $sudo systemctl stop <service_name>
syntax to auto-start a service:-             $sudo systemctl restart <service_name>
